  "_exec_summary": [
    {
      "ESSeqNum": 0,
      "FacilityID": 1000045351,
      "SummaryText": "Accidental Release Prevention and Emergency Response Policies\n\n\n\nMatheson Tri-Gas, Inc. is committed to the safety of its employees and neighbors and operates the facility as a responsible member of the community. Matheson Tri-Gas, Inc. encourages personnel to continually identify methods and procedures to reduce the use and risks associated with hazardous chemicals. This process includes protecting the community, environment, and personnel by implementing technology and procedures designed to reduce the impact of any potential release of toxic chemicals. This commitment to safety is documented in the policy and compliance manuals for this facility, which are available to all employees.\n\n\n\nAs part of Matheson Tri-Gas, Inc.'s commitment to safe and environmentally friendly operations, monthly meetings are conducted with all employees as well as other more specific operational meetings concerning safety. Input and comments from plant personnel are also key aspects of Matheson Tri-Gas, Inc.'s safety practices: By giving personnel the ability to make suggestions regarding safety and operational practices, the facility can operate efficiently and safely. Another key element in Matheson Tri-Gas, Inc.'s safety practices consists of the regular internal and third party environmental and safety audits.\n\n\n\nRegulated Substances\n\n\n\nThe Matheson Tri-Gas, Inc. facility receives, stores, manufactures, and ships the following regulated chemicals: n-Butane, 1-Butene, Ethylene, Isobutane, Isopentane, Methane, n-Pentane, Propane, and Propylene. These chemicals are regulated at the Program 3 level.\n\n\n\nGeneral Accidental Release Prevention Programs and Prevention Steps\n\n\n\nAs part of the implementation of the PSM/RMP, elements of the prevention programs have been developed to manage process safety issues associated with the facility. Each of the program elements have been developed according to OSHA and EPA regulations in order to ensure safe operating practices and conditions at the Mat"
    },
    {
      "ESSeqNum": 1,
      "FacilityID": 1000045351,
      "SummaryText": "heson Tri-Gas, Inc. facility.\n\n\n\nPrevention 3 Elements:\n\n\n\nProcess Safety Information - information regarding the hazards each chemical, process descriptions, and equipment properties.\n\n\n\nProcess Hazards Analysis - a detailed review of the process and recommendations to improve the safety of the system.\n\n\n\nOperating Procedures - procedures designed to comply with regulations and provide safe practices for the system.\n\n\n\nTraining - procedures and logs for personnel training on the covered processes. \n\n\n\nMechanical Integrity - manufacturer recommended maintenance procedures, schedules, and documentation. \n\n\n\nManagement of Change - documentation and tracking of changes that affect the process involving the regulated chemicals.\n\n\n\nPre-Startup Safety Review - prior to the startup of a new regulated process or major changes to the existing process, a review will be conducted as required by the PSM/RMP regulations. \n\n\n\nCompliance Audits - documentation of tri-annual audits of the covered process. \n\n\n\nIncident Investigation - documentation and investigation procedures for determining and mitigating releases.\n\n\n\nEmployee Participation - documentation and statement of Matheson Tri-Gas, Inc.'s commitment to providing a safe and open work place.\n\n\n\nHot Work Permit - procedures for documenting and safely performing work on or near process equipment during normal operations. \n\n\n\nContractors - policy for contractors and outside vendors that work on or near the regulated process. \n\n\n\nThese elements are continually updated and reviewed through the Management System at Matheson Tri-Gas, Inc. The Management System includes planning, organizing, implementing, and controlling different aspects of the plan.\n\n\n\nFive Year Accident History \n\n\n\nEPA's RMP Program defines \"accident\" as the following:\n\n\n\n\"The release must be from a covered process and involve a regulated substance held above its threshold quantity in the process.\n\n\n\nThe release must have caused at least one of the following:\n\n\n"
    },
    {
      "ESSeqNum": 2,
      "FacilityID": 1000045351,
      "SummaryText": "\n?    On-site deaths, injuries, or significant property damage (?68.42(a)); or\n\n?    Known offsite deaths, injuries, property damage, environmental damage, evacuations, or sheltering in place (?68.42(a)).\"\n\n\n\nA review of the facility's five year accident history (October 2008 - October 2013) revealed that there have been no releases of any of the regulated substances that meet the RMP definition of \"accident\" as described above. \n\n\n\nEmergency Action Plan \n\n\n\nMatheson Tri-Gas, Inc. has implemented a corporate Emergency Action Plan, which includes emergency and evacuation procedures, safety and health considerations, and notification procedures.\n\n\n\nPlanned Changes\n\n\n\nChanges determined by the Process Hazard Analysis and consideration made during the development of this plan will be conducted in a timely manner. The PSM/RMP will be updated at least every five years and is due to be updated on the five year anniversary of the PHA study (May 2014). The PSM/RMP will also be updated within six months in the event of a change which requires a new Process Hazard Analysis."
    }
  ]
